Hungary (35.6), Bulgaria (35.4), Estonia (32.6), the Czech Republic (32.5), Poland (31.7), Finland (31.1), Serbia (30.6) and Denmark (30.4) make the top 10 on the list, while on the other end of the table are Russia (5.2); Spain (5.1), Cyprus, France and the UK with 4.2; Monaco with 4.1 and the Netherlands with 3.8.

Orbán’s tweet was a response to the latest report in The Guardian, which revealed a plan to install 5G base stations in Hungary without public debate or regulatory oversight. The full report can be accessed here.

The name of the event was not decided by using the most direct method, which would have been to call it the “IMF”, but rather by allying it with the Bank’s desired direction of monetary policy towards a target inflation rate of 2%.
